The Future.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://news.bbc.co.uk/olmedia/1940000/images/_1943837_sun300.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br><br>What are the hallmarks of a superpower or leading nation? The highest internationally acknowledged achievements possible. They are the two greatest technological breakthroughs generally accepted to have been made in modern times. Nuclear power, both fission and fusion is one. Splitting the atom is now reserved for a select group of nations. The other is spaceflight. Only two nations have actually put men into space.<br>Unfortunately, both of these cutting edge technologies suffer from public perceptions. Nuclear power is feared. Spaceflight is seen as dull. Both these fields of endeavour and their huge potential for positively impacting our lives are largely ignored. Only in fiction do we get a glimpse of what might be possible should we embrace the future. Together, these two technologies joined could give us unparalleled  access to space. Affordable airline like access to space. <br>  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=moybin>moybin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/8/02 4:06:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  RE: The Future</span><hr size=1> Where to start?  Perhaps the largest barrier to scientific advancement is the requirement to think.  I'm pushing 51 years of age.  My high school education was equal to if not exceeding what most college graduates receive today.  Education in the USA has taken an abyssmal turn for the worse in the last 1/4 century.  So if you aren't very good at working through complex thought processes, you won't have a desire to understand complex world processes.<br><br>Or there's the genetic answer: some people are born stupid and lose ground from there.  The politicians love these folks: it's easy to control stupid people.  Smart people ask questions.  Sometimes questions the politicos don't know the answers to, after all, most of them are ex-lawyers, and you get to be a lawyer because you couldn't handle calculus (scratch engineering), didn't like blood (scratch MD), didn't like big tables of numbers (scratch accounting).  So lawyer is a default career.<br><br>The single biggest stumbling block to nuclear energy is the Atomic Energy Act of 1954.  It locked away as SECRET almost all of the information now readily available on the internet.  My father has two degrees: electrical engineer and optometrist.  By today's standard, he should be f$%king brilliant.  I went to Nuke School in the navy as an enlisted person, no college.  His very first question to me was &quot;can they blow up&quot; meaning Naval nuclear reactors and big mushroom clouds.<br><br>He SHOULD have had enough information available to let his education tell him this was physically impossible.  The Atomic Energy Act of 1954 made sure he was IGNORANT (not stupid) of the facts.<br><br>Then Hollywood came along and filled in the holes left by higher education when it came to superstitions.  Superstitions should have gone the way of the Dodo, but instead, people are afraid of being turned into a green superstrong monster, or being devoured by giant ants.  <br><br>I have come to rationalize the situation this way: The USA has about 1/4 of the world's uranium stored away in undeveloped mines.  When all the dead dinosaur runs out, and it will, and coal is still too dirty to burn, the USA will have a clean fuel just waiting to be used.  Necessity being the Mother that she is, people won't care about radiation or all that other nonsense.  They will want something to act as go-juice in their cars and planes, and they will want their microwaves and 3D video boxes to work.  Period.  I figure that will be around 3000AD.  Between then and now, we will fight a war for the coal and oil and natural gas that lies buried under the Antarctic ice shelfs.  <br><br>Of course the ice will be gone by then, but it will still get plenty cold down there, just the same.  Only a few countries maintain the ability to fight wars in arctic conditions, ever wonder why?<br><br>Lastly, let's just say we figure out a cheap, reliable means to get into space and move about freely in the Solar System.  What happens to Earth?  Or to any one country on Earth?  History is a pretty good teacher here, though no one studies history anymore.<br><br>When 2 new continents opened up 600 years ago, the best, brightest, and most driven of Europe bailed out and went West.  Europe has never recovered from that exodus, and the subsequent floods of people.  The same thing will happen if space opens up.<br><br>Move an asteroid into synchronous orbit, start smelting and refining all the metals in it, and watch the world metals markets crash.  Labor layoffs, mass riots because offworld steel, gold, lead, platinum, you name it, has crashed the value of Earth-mined metals.  Only the Sierra Club will be happy because the pollution will be in space, and no strip mining.  Though they will bitch because an asteroid that close will mess up the Ansel Adams poster shots of Yosemite.<br><br>The short term problem is getting into space for real.  The long term problem will be the stragglers that don't want to leave Earth, no how, no way, and their constant bitching that the visionaries are ruining things.  They are the same people that bitched about horseless carriages while standing knee deep in horse @#%$ in downtown New York City. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 widt